From Todd Stark Subject Re OCD This is to followup my previous reply on this topic which it has been pointed out to me might have been dangerously misleading in two I stated that psychotherapy meaning talking therapy and so on was used to treat Obsessive Compulsive Disorder which though sometimes true is It is not often found effective particularly by Primary treatment today usually consists at least in part of drug The most current theories of this condition attribute it to more to biological causes than psychological in places where this distinction becomes I mentioned that the DSM IIIR mentions 'impulses' as a possible diagnostic However this might look like something people associate with psychotic conditions uncontrollable or unpredictable behaviors which is NOT the case with One of the diagnostic criteria of OCD is that the individual can and does suppress some of their 'impulses ' although they are an unending source of The obsessive thoughts and ritualistic actions usually associated with OCD are most frequently very mundane and predictable closer to a superstitious nature than a dangerous nature for the most Some references one non technical and several technical that someone was kind enough to supply for me but was unable to post themself The boy who couldn't stop washing by judith technical refs pharmacotherapy of o c disorder donna m jermain and lynn crismon pharmacotherapy epidemiology of ocd seteven a rasmussen and jane eisen j clin psychiatry the waking nightmare an overview of ocd judith l rapoport j clin psychiatry absence of placebo response in ocd matig r mavissakalian bruce jones stephen olson j nerv ment disease vol And thanks very much to those who supplied constructive criticism to my first post on I hope this helps clarify the parts that were kind regards todd Todd Stark Digital Equipment Corporation Philadelphia USA A word is the skin of a living thought Olliver Wendell Holmes